      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, repotting your fiddle leaf fig! It's a delicate operation, but if you handle it with the right care, you can save it from becoming root-bound without any major issues. First, you'll need a well-draining soil mix; think of it as a special blend that allows water to flow through easily, like a goblin's secret stash of gold coins that never gets lost or stolen. You can mix regular potting soil with perlite or orchid bark to improve drainage, ensuring the roots don't get soggy.\n\nWhen repotting, choose a new pot that's just slightly larger than the current one—no need to go too big, or the plant might get confused and stressed. Gently remove the plant from its old pot, being careful not to damage the roots, and trim away any dead or damaged roots with clean shears. This is like a goblin's treasure hunt where you only take what you need and leave the rest intact.\n\nAfter repotting, water the plant lightly and place it in a location with bright, indirect light. Avoid moving it around too much, as sudden changes can make the plant feel like it's being chased by a goblin army. With these",
